05560nam a22010095i 9780691221199DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912211997 a10.1515/97806912211992doi  a(DE-B1597)572621  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aRA395.A3bH33 1997 7aPOL0160002bisacsh04a362.1/09732201 aHacker, Jacob S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Road to Nowhere :bThe Genesis of President Clinton's Plan for Health Security /cJacob S. Hacker. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b9 line illus. 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in American Politics: Historical, International, and Comparative Perspectives ;v17500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Puzzle -- tChapter 1. The Rise of Reform -- tChapter 2. A Prescription for Reform -- tChapter 3. The Liberal Synthesis -- tChapter 4. The Campaign -- tChapter 5. The Plan -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. Methodology -- tAppendix B. Jackson Hole Participants, 1990-1992 -- tAppendix C. California Insurance Commissioner's Health Care Advisory Committee -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the 1992 presidential campaign, health care reform became a hot issue, paving the way for one of the most important yet ill-fated social policy initiatives in American history: Bill Clinton's 1993 proposal for comprehensive coverage under "managed competition." Here Jacob Hacker not only investigates for the first time how managed competition became the president's reform framework, but also illuminates how issues and policies emerge. He follows Clinton's policy ideas from their initial formulation by policy experts through their endorsement by medical industry leaders and politicians to their inclusion--in a new and unexpected form--in the proposal itself. Throughout he explores key questions: Why did health reform become a national issue in the 1990s? Why did Clinton choose managed competition over more familiar options during the 1992 presidential campaign? What effect did this have on the fate of his proposal? Drawing on records of the President's task force, interviews with a wide range of key policy players, and many other sources, Hacker locates his analysis within the context of current political theories on agenda setting. He concludes that Clinton chose managed competition partly because advocates inside and outside the campaign convinced him that it represented a unique middle road to health care reform. This conviction, Hacker maintains, blinded the president and his allies to the political risks of the approach and hindered the development of an effective strategy for enacting it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHealth care reformzUnited States. 0aManaged care plans (Medical care)zUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Medical Association (AMA).  aAmerican Prospect.  aBergthold, Linda.  aBrookings Institution.  aCarville, James.  aConsumers Union.  aDaschle, Tom.  aEnthoven, Alain.  aGaramendi plan.  aGreenberg, Stan.  aHeritage Foundation.  aJohnson, Lyndon.  aKennedy, Ted.  aKingdon, John.  aMayhew, David.  aMitchell, George.  aNew Democrats.  aThorpe, Kenneth.  aWofford, Harris.  aelite opinion.  afocusing events.  ainflation, medical.  airon triangles.  aleadership: congressional.  aorganized anarchies.  apayroll taxes.  arationalizing politics.  aself-insurance health plans.  autilization review.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Unive